gmd:abstract.gco:CharacterString: The numerical model is built using an high resolution (1m) idealized domain to test the implementation of lateral retreat formulations in the COAWST modeling framework. The lateral retreat is calculated within the model and is based on lateral wave thrust.

gmd:purpose.gco:CharacterString: The model domain was developed to test the implementation of lateral retreat formulations within COAWST that lead to a change of marsh cell to an open water cell. These model results may also be reused to support any prospective research work where appropriate.

gmd:credit.gco:CharacterString: This study was part of the USGS Coastal and Marine Hazards and Resources Program.

gmd:otherConstraints.gco:CharacterString: Please cite this as: Kalra, T.S., Ganju, N.K., and Arextxabaleta, A.L., 2021, Idealized numerical model for marsh lateral wave thrust and retreat: U.S. Geological Survey data release, https://doi.org/FILL

gmd:description.gco:CharacterString: In this work, we implement two new marsh dynamics processes in the 3-D COAWST modeling framework. The processes included are the erosion of the marsh edge scarp caused by lateral wave thrust from surface waves and vertical accretion driven by organic growth on the marsh platform. The process of vertical accretion occurs due to biomass production and is calculated by fitting a parabolic productivity curve between mean high water and maximum vegetation depth for a given tidal range. Please cite this as: Kalra, T.S., Ganju, N.K., Arextaxabelta, A.L., Carr, J., Defne, Z., and Moriarty, J.M.,: Modeling Marsh Dynamics Using a 3-D Coupled Wave-Flow-Sediment Model, https://doi.org/FILL, in review, 2021.

gmd:supplementalInformation.gco:CharacterString: The model has Arakawa C-grid type staggered grids for each of the following; grid cell centers, cell-edge mid-points, and corners. Grid cells are of irregular sizes but are rectangular with maximum orthogonality while conforming to the curvilinear shape of the grid. Generally, vector quantities such as velocity are calculated at cell edges, whereas the scalar quantities such as density are calculated at cell centers. Geospatial vertical resolution is variable due to the sigma coordinate system of the numerical model.
